attribution.changeMessage: The record is in the Church Book for Avnslev, Vindinge, Svensborg.  Familysearch's standardized place name is Skalkendrup, Aunslev, Vindinge, Svendborg, Denmark.  I am uncertain if "Aunslev" is a typo.  The record is a Baptism/Christening record on Palm Sunday in March of 1788 and they are using the "church holiday" system of dating.  In 1788 on the Danish calender, the full moon is 22 March so Easter Sunday is 23 March and Palm Sunday is on 16 March 1788.
See Church record.
Date of birth is calculated from his age at burial.  The birth place is extracted from the journal of Hans Dinesen.
The Church Records are of Baptism, Marriage and Burial.  Sometimes they also contain a birth date or a death date.  I this case only the date of burial is recorded.

In the birth/baptism record her name is Marie.  At this date, patronymics was in full sway so her name was Marie Rasmussen at birth.  When she is confirmed in 1836, her name is given as Marie Dinersen.  Confirmation is often the first record where a child has a last name.
See source below.

facts.value: Confirmation in the Danish Lutheran Church

attribution.changeMessage: She is listed as the mother of Hans Villiam Hansen, who was born 30 April 1855, in Gentofte, København, Denmark.  Actually he was born 6 October 1854, baptised 30 April 1855.  She is in the 1855 Danish census that was taken 1 February 1855 and her husband is a widower in the 1860 census also taken 1 February 1860.  Have ordered the Danish mission records microfilm # 41943, will see if that produces a date.
This is an Americanized spelling and the name that descended down through my family.

This is the original Danish spelling. This is the spelling on the 1900 US Census.  At the time of his birth, patronymics was still in force so his surname would have been Rasmussen.  He used the name Dinesen in the United States.  He is very specific in his journal that the name was and should remain spelled "Dinesen".  His children did not  maintain the name or spelling, consequently there are several variations of the name being used today.
This is an Americanized spelling.
See source below.

attribution.changeMessage: In the burial record it says 12 January 1819 burial, there is no death date.  There is no birth/baptism record.  Burial record also says "Rasmus Dinessen Dodfodl son" - "Dodfodl" is stillborn.  There is also no age given.  All of this tells me this was a true stillbirth and not a short term infant death
